summary.seg: Emmanuel College MS 33 is a Miscellany of Greek texts comprising four parts, some of which recur in Emmanuel College MS 32.
Part I came from a larger manuscript of Pindar, the first part of which has been identified as Oxford, Bodleian Library, Barocci MS 46.

All three remaining parts consist of one quire each. Two of them come from manuscripts whose parts have been divided between Emmanuel MS 32 and 33. Part II is the sixth quire of a manuscript of Alexandra by Lycophoron, four quires are of which are now in Emmanuel MS 32 Part III (ff. 48r-78v). Part IV completes the Posthomerica by Quintus Smyrnaeus and should follow Emmanuel MS 32 Part VII, f. 166v.

condition.p: In fair condition. There have been losses from and softening to the edges of Part I (see below).

binding.p: 17th-century full leather binding over pulpboard, sewn with cord on single raised supports, separate pastedowns of plain paper with stubs and separate sewn endleaves. Boards are attached with laced-in slips. There is decorative blind tooling on the boards and spine, and the former classmark MS 1.2.12 appears on patches on the spine.
binding.condition: Both outer joints are partially split at head and tail.

history.acquisition: The date of acquisition is unknown. It is listed in Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697), Pars I tom. III, p. 92 n. 131.

recordHist.source: Description (2021) draws on M.R. James, The Western manuscripts in the library of Emmanuel College: a descriptive catalogue, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1904, p. 34-35.

msItem.explicit: f. [93]v Νεμέας Ἐπιδαυρόθεν τ’ ἄπο καὶ Μεγάρων δέδορκεν φάος

support.material: ff. [1]-[94] Western paper, folded in quarto. Watermark: Hat ( c. 60 50 ) in the gutter, similar to Harlfinger, Chapeau 55. This example is dated to 1516.

collation.p: This part consists of 12 quires, all quaternions. The sixth original quire is missing with loss of text.

list.item: Quire 18-2 ff. [1-6] The first and last folios have been lost, with loss of text.

signatures.p: Signatures in Greek numerals in brown ink on the first recto, lower margin of quires 2-11 (Pythian odes), from βʹ to ιβʹ, and last verso, lower margin of quires 3-5, 7-8, 10-11. The quire ϛʹ is missing.
Signatures in Arabic numerals in dark brown ink by a later hand on first recto, upper internal corner of quires 2-11 from f. 7r.

supportDesc.condition: There have been losses from and softening to the edges of ff. [1-6], which have been repaired with Japanese paper. There is mild water staining and there are some areas of dirt.

layoutDesc.layout:
ff. [1]r-[94]v A single column of 10 lines. 124 70
Lines for marginal commentary have been ruled in hardpoint in all three margins, but no text has been written here.

handNote.p: Hand A: a calligraphic minuscule very similar to the one of Andreas Donos in Emmanuel MS 32, Part I ff. 1r-[16]v. This hand has been ascribed to an helper of the Cretan scribe, probably Petros Daklozaos from Rethymnon (Πέτρος ὁ Δακλωζάος ὁ Ῥηθυμναῖος; cf. Ciccolella 2017, p. 380 n. 38).

additions.p: Content references and missing lines added by a reader in black ink.

history.origin: This Part was produced in the early 16th century, not before ca. 1516.

handNote.p: Hand B: ff. 95r-[102]v, upright mixed minuscule, with marked variation in letter size and aesthetical efforts. Ligatures, abbreviations and inclusion are widely in use.
Mute iota is in use. Breathings are curved; accents do not join to letters or breathings.

history.origin: The characteristics of the script and the watermark suggest that this part was produced in the early 16th century.
